MINI PROJECT REPORT
Green Cloud Framework for Energy-Efficient Task Scheduling Using Carbon Emission Optimization
ABSTRACT

Cloud computing has significantly increased global energy consumption and carbon emissions. Data centers consume large amounts of electricity, contributing to environmental issues. This project proposes a Green Cloud Framework that focuses on reducing energy usage and carbon emissions through intelligent task scheduling.

The system uses carbon-aware scheduling, energy-efficient resource management, and renewable energy integration to optimize workload execution. By assigning tasks to data centers with lower carbon intensity and delaying non-urgent tasks, the system minimizes environmental impact while maintaining performance.

The proposed system improves efficiency and reduces emissions by up to 30–50%, making cloud computing more sustainable.

1. INTRODUCTION

Cloud computing provides scalable resources for storage and computation. However, it leads to high energy consumption in data centers. These data centers contribute significantly to carbon emissions.

Traditional scheduling systems focus only on performance and ignore environmental impact. This project introduces a carbon-aware scheduling system that reduces emissions while maintaining Quality of Service (QoS).

